Either way; keep up the great work---you're a master of ingenuity

replies.text:
@sonic_P I am not sure whether the loss will be really immense or minimal. The best way is to try and see. That is why I asked Robert, if he had any comparative values. I am rather optimistic and see this method (not only this design) as the most efficient VAWT to be designed. HAWT is much more efficient than any VAWT due to its logic. For  HAWT, as ypou said, the wind is parallel to the rotation axis, and the whole fan area is productive, while for "normal" VAWT the wind is perpendicular, and halfof  the area is not productive, if not counter-productive.

But with this design you change the wind direction ( and just be because it is parallel  to the axis, it doesn not make it HAWT; but yes a HAWT rotated 90 degrees with wind also diverted.) and make use of the whole area again, while you loose some power due to re-direction.

That is what I am after.

@sonic_P It is nice that you have some background on the subject, VAWTs in particular.  I am not  (professionally at least) involved in the subject matter, but heavily interseted, especially on VAWTs; for use on boats. As far as I know lift type VAWTs are more performant than drag type ones; so your system should be on the upper scale VAWTs; but still as I said it can make use of the half of the wind swept area. That is why HAWTs are aup to 40% efficient while VAWT stay below 20% level.

If in this design, power loss is even at about 50% level, then that would be at other VAWTs' efficiensy level. Any better preformance will put this thing  above them.

It is not that easy to sit down and solve partial differential equations on paper to see how much it will perform; and not everybody might have the chance to sit down and model the system for CFD overnight. Just making a small model might be faster and easier...

@ThinkingandTinkering I currently have a mini solar system running 12v and 5v power supplies in my garage, just enough for simple LED lighting and phone charging. this wind turbine project of yours may well end up as the reason I buy a 3D printer and make some little wind turbines in addition to the solar rig.
keep up the good work Sir!
Mike
